<div id="Story3" style="padding:0 12px;box-sizing:border-box;">
                <div class="section_heading" style="width:100%; background-color: transparent;box-sizing:border-box;padding-bottom:12px;">
                    <div id="web3" style="width:100%;max-width:115px;height:1px;background-color:#D3D3D3;margin:24px auto; ">
                    </div>
                    <h3 style="padding:0;width:100%;font-family:Georgia, 'Times New Roman', Times, serif;font-weight:700;font-size:16px;color:#93888F;line-height:23.1px;text-align: left;margin:0;text-transform:uppercase;">Mobility</h3>
                </div>
                <div style="width:100%; background-color: transparent; box-sizing:border-box;">
                    <h3 style="width:100%; font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;font-size:16px;margin:0;padding-bottom:16px;font-weight:700;color:#28121F;line-height:20px;text-transform:capitalize;letter-spacing:-0.32px;text-align:left;box-sizing:border-box;">BYD now controls 35% of Africa EV market, report says</h3>
                    <div style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size:16px;line-height:25.6px;margin:0;padding-bottom:16px;box-sizing:border-box;">
<figure style="width: 100%;padding-bottom:16px;text-align:left;margin:0">


                        <a href="https://techcabal.com/category/newsletters/tc-daily/">
                             <img decoding="async" 
     	loading="lazy" src="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/06/24BYD1_21775ebfb1c4e50841e15d37f3eb92cc.jpg" width="100%" height="auto" style="object-fit: cover"></a>
                         <figcaption style="color:#808080;font-size:12px;font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;line-height:19.8px;padding-top:6px;font-weight:400">Image Source: Dealerfloor</figcaption>
                    </figure>
                        
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">If you own a BYD electric vehicle (EV) in Africa, you&rsquo;re one of the customers driving the Chinese company&rsquo;s dominance in the continent&rsquo;s electric vehicle market.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">According to a report by the International Energy Agency (IEA), BYD&rsquo;s share of <a href="https://www.ecofinagency.com/news-industry/0206-56095-byd-captures-35-of-africas-ev-market-emerging-as-a-leading-player" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">Africa&rsquo;s EV market</a> surged from 4% in 2023 to 35% in 2025, showing how quickly the company has scaled across emerging markets.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;"><strong>Why is BYD growing this fast? </strong>While Africa&#8217;s EV market still has far lower uptake than petrol cars, BYD is attracting a growing base of loyal customers. In 2025, BYD car sales grew from 4,000 vehicles in 2023 to nearly 25,000 in 2025, with Egypt, Morocco and South Africa accounting for almost 70% of total demand.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;"><strong>State of play: </strong>Buying a brand new EV is not cheap, even for many African markets with slightly better disposable income. BYD has intentionally targeted that group by shipping cheaper EV models in markets like Egypt and South Africa, <a href="https://techcentral.co.za/electric-cars-for-sale-in-south-africa/257624/" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">undercutting competitors</a> like Maxus and Toyota, which recently <a href="https://techcentral.co.za/toyota-plugs-in-at-last-bz4x-is-its-first-ev-for-south-africa/281479/" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">introduced an EV</a> in the market.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;">BYD&rsquo;s expansion is also being backed by aggressive infrastructure plans in South Africa, the continent&rsquo;s most developed auto market. In April, the company <a href="https://www.reuters.com/world/asia-pacific/byd-accelerates-south-africa-expansion-with-more-dealerships-planned-2026-2025-12-04/" style="text-decoration: underline; color: #b61313 !important;">opened 32 new dealerships</a> in the country, and plans to deploy between 200 and 300 fast-charging stations by the end of the year, positioning the country as a potential launchpad for wider African growth.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;"><strong>Between the lines: </strong>The broader trend points to a market that is still concentrated but becoming competitive, with Chinese automakers rapidly gaining ground as EV adoption begins to take hold in a handful of key economies.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0;"><strong>Zoom out: </strong>For now, BYD&rsquo;s dominance reflects scale and speed. Whether that advantage holds will depend on how quickly infrastructure, affordability, and policy support expand beyond a few urban centres.</p>
</div>
